\begin{verbatim}
EMAMdofProblem(frf, freq; frange = [freq[1], freq[end]])
\end{verbatim}
Data structure defining the inputs for EMA-MDOF modal extraction methods.

\textbf{Constructor parameters}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{frf::Array\{Complex,3\}}: 3D array of Frequency Response Functions (FRF) (array nm x ne x nf)


\item \texttt{freq::AbstractArray\{Real\}}: Vector of frequency values (Hz)


\item \texttt{frange::Vector\{Real\}}: Frequency range for analysis (default: [freq[1], freq[end]])

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{frf::Array\{Complex, 3\}}: 3D array of Frequency Response Functions (FRF) (array nm x ne x nf)


\item \texttt{freq::AbstractArray\{Real\}}: Vector of frequency values (Hz)

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
AutoEMAMdofProblem(prob, dpi, method; modetype)
\end{verbatim}
Structure containing the input data for automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAMdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{order::Int}: Model order (number of poles to extract)


\item \texttt{dpi::Vector\{Int\}}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{method::MdofModalExtraction}: Method to extract the poles

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{PeakPicking}: Peak picking method (default)


\item \texttt{CircleFit}: Circle fitting method


\item \texttt{LSFit}: Least squares fitting method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{modetype::Symbol}: Type of mode shapes to extract

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:real}: Real mode shapes (default)


\item \texttt{:complex}: Complex mode shapes

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
EMAMdofSolution(poles, ϕn)
\end{verbatim}
Structure containing the solution of the automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles}: Extracted poles


\item \texttt{ms}: Mode shapes

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
EMAMdofStabilization(prob, poles, modefn, mode_stabfn, mode_stabdr)
\end{verbatim}
Data structure summarizing the results of the stabilization analysis.

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAMdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{frange::Vector\{Real\}}: Frequency range used for the stabilization analysis


\item \texttt{poles::Vector\{Vector\{Complex\}\}}: Vector of vectors containing extracted poles at each model order


\item \texttt{modefn::Matrix\{Real\}}: Matrix containing the natural frequencies (useful for plotting)


\item \texttt{mode\_stabfn::Matrix\{Bool\}}: Matrix indicating the stability of natural frequencies


\item \texttt{mode\_stabdr::Matrix\{Bool\}}: Matrix indicating the stability of damping ratios

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

This structure is returned by the \texttt{stabilization} function after performing a stabilization diagram analysis and used by \texttt{stabilization\_plot} for visualization.

\begin{verbatim}
poles_extraction(prob, order, method = LSCF(); stabdiag = false)
\end{verbatim}
Extract complex poles from Frequency Response Function (FRF) data using the specified modal extraction method.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAMdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{order::Int}: Model order (number of poles to extract)


\item \texttt{method}: Modal extraction method

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCE()}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method


\item \texttt{LSCF()}: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default)


\item \texttt{PLSCF()}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{stabdiag}: Boolean to indicate the function is used to build a stability diagram (default: false)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of extracted complex poles

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

The \texttt{weighting} parameter is only applicable for the LSCF and PLSCF methods.

\begin{verbatim}
stabilization(prob, max_order, method; weighting = true, stabcrit = [0.01, 0.05])
\end{verbatim}
Perform stabilization diagram analysis using the specified modal extraction method (LSCE, LSCF, or PLSCF).

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAMdofProblem}: EMA-MDOF problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{max\_order::Int}: Maximum model order for the stabilization analysis


\item \texttt{method}: Modal extraction method to use

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCE()}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method


\item \texttt{LSCF()}: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default)


\item \texttt{PLSCF()}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{frange}: Frequency range for analysis (default: [freq[1], freq[end]])


\item \texttt{weighting}: Boolean to indicate if the weighting based on the variance of each FRF is applied (default: true)


\item \texttt{stabcrit}: Vector containing the stability criteria for natural frequencies and damping ratios (default: [0.01, 0.05])

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{sol}: Data structure containing the results of the stabilization analysis

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
stabilization_plot(stab::EMAMdofStabilization, indicator = :psif; type = :dis)
\end{verbatim}
Plot stabilization diagram for EMA-MDOF pole stability analysis.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{stab}: EMA-MDOF stabilization data


\item \texttt{indicator}: Indicator to plot

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:psif} : Power spectrum indicator function


\item \texttt{:cmif} : Complex mode indicator function

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{type}: Type of FRF (for CMIF calculation)

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:dis} : Displacement (default)


\item \texttt{:vel} : Velocity


\item \texttt{:acc} : Acceleration

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{fig}: Figure

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
mode_residues(frf, freq, poles; frange = [freq[1], freq[end]], type = :dis)
\end{verbatim}
Compute residues and lower and upper residuals of a frequency response function (FRF) given its poles.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob}: EMAMdofProblem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Keyword Arguments}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{frange}: Frequency range for residue calculation (default: full range)


\item \texttt{type}: Type of FRF

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:dis}: Admittance (default)


\item \texttt{:vel}: Mobility


\item \texttt{:acc}: Accelerance

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{res}: Residues corresponding to each pole


\item \texttt{lr}: Lower residual


\item \texttt{ur}: Upper residual

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
modeshape_extraction(residues, poles, di = [1, 1]; type = :complex)
\end{verbatim}
Extract mode shapes using MDOF approximation

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{residues}: Residues matrix of size (np, nm, ne)


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles


\item \texttt{dpi}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{type}: Type of mode shape

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:complex}: Complex mode shapes (default)


\item \texttt{:real}: Real mode shapes

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{ϕ}: Mode shapes matrix


\item \texttt{ci}: Scaling factors vector

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
solve(prob::AutoEMAMdofProblem)
\end{verbatim}
Solve automatically experimental modal analysis problem using Mdof methods

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob\_ema}: Structure containing the input data for automatic experimental modal analysis using Mdof methods

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{sol}: Solution of problem:

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles}: Extracted poles


\item \texttt{ms}: Real mode shapes

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
